Aim
To extract metadata from files using ExifTool and identify information such as file type, file size, and
modification details.
Introduction
Metadata is hidden information stored inside files that contains details such as file name, file type, creation
date, author information, and software details.
ExifTool is a command-line utility used to read and analyze metadata from documents, images, and
multimedia files. Metadata extraction is useful in cybersecurity and digital forensics for identifying hidden
information inside files.
Procedure
Step 1: Install ExifTool
Open Kali Linux terminal and install ExifTool:
sudo apt install libimage-exiftool-perl -y
Step 2: Verify Installation
Check whether ExifTool is installed successfully:
exiftool -ver
Step 3: Create Working Directory
Create a directory for metadata analysis:
mkdir metadata
Move into the directory:
cd metadata
Step 4: Create Sample File
Create a sample text file:
echo "Hello World" > sample.txt
Check the file:
ls
Step 5: Extract Metadata
Run the following command:
exiftool sample.txt
Implementation
Command Used
exiftool sample.txt
Explanation
• exiftool → Metadata extraction tool
• sample.txt → Target file
Output
File Name : sample.txt
File Type : TXT
File Size : 12 bytes
MIME Type : text/plain
Word Count : 2
Analysis
The extracted metadata contains:
• File name
• File type
• File size
• MIME type
• Word count
This information is useful in forensic investigation and file analysis.
Result
Thus, metadata was extracted successfully from the file using ExifTool.
